# -*- mode:org;coding:utf-8 -*-
#+TITLE: interactors — design revision: singleton interactors, activation state, stack manipulation
#+AUTHOR: Pascal J. Bourguignon
#+DATE: 2026-07-15

Record of the design discussion revising the interactor implementation
(follow-up of =interactor-unification.issue=; supersedes parts of what
1.4.39–1.4.41 implemented). To be revised by pjb before implementation.

* Purpose

The interactor stack exists to SIMPLIFY code by systematizing behavior
across the interaction modules (REPL, debugger, navigators, inspector,
editor): one INTERACTOR-LOOP, one command-resolution rule over the
stack, one read-eval-print. Changing the current interactor should in
most cases be a *stack manipulation inside the running loop* — push,
pop, swap — with a NEW (nested) loop only where the control flow is
genuinely re-entrant (invoke-debugger, which must return a resume
directive to the engine).

* Decisions

** D1. Interactors are singletons; no COPY-INTERACTOR.

An interactor is *program*, not state: name, alias, dictionaries,
reader/evaluator/prompt/status behavior, on-result convention. Commands
— clautolisp-provided or user-defined — are functions ("compiled
program"), not state data; mutating a user dictionary between two
activations is program redefinition, not state. Nothing is copied per
entry. (The 1.4.39 per-entry COPY-INTERACTOR instances and the STATE
slot on the struct are to be removed; see T1 for where activation state
goes.)

** D2. Context flows through dynamic variables and one read-eval-print.

- The UI / session / hit reach command bodies through the existing
  thread-global dynamic variables (=*debugger-ui*= /
  =*debugger-session*= / =*debugger-hit*=), not through closures stored
  in interactor slots.
- The dialect is NOT interactor state. It influences only the
  read-eval-print. There is ONE read-eval-print entry (runtime),
  consulting the session's *current* dialect at each use and
  parameterized only by where to evaluate (globally vs in the selected
  frame). Every interactor's sexp path routes through it: the REPL, a
  =(FORM)= at DBG>/NAV>, the inspector's =e= and bare forms, sedit's
  =e=. (Also fixes a pre-existing wart: repl-loop captures the dialect
  lexically at entry, so a mid-session =*AUTOLISP-DIALECT*= change is
  not honored by the reader; and cmd-eval's read does not obviously go
  through the session dialect.)

** D3. Names and aliases.

- The bottom interactor is named "AUTOLISP" with alias "LISP".
- The prompt is late-bound (the interactor's prompt function), so it
  stays =_$= for now and can later e.g. indicate the current dialect.
- ALDO keeps alias "debug".

** D4. LAVI is a separate interactor.

NAVI and LAVI are two interactors; the =navigator= setting decides
which one a stop (or =nav=) pushes, and switching between them is a
command that pops one and pushes the other — a stack manipulation in
the SAME loop.

** D5. Commands may reuse functions across interactors.

Two interactors can attach commands to the same function — or to
different functions under the same key: NAVI's motions skip to
poll-points while SEDIT's traverse ALL sub-sexps, so the motions are
DIFFERENT functions under the same keys; other commands can share one
function. Registration must therefore accept a *function (designator)*
as well as an inline body. (Note: =BIND-COMMAND= — the function-form
registrar under =DEFINE-COMMAND= — already takes a function; what is
missing is only the sugar, e.g. a =:function NAME= variant of
DEFINE-COMMAND, and a documented calling convention shared functions
can rely on; see T3.)

** D6. User dictionaries are strictly per interactor.

There is NO global user-command table. =*global-dictionary*= (which
operationally always was ALDO's user dictionary) is retired into
=(interactor-user-commands *aldo*)=. A "global" user command is simply
one defined on the AUTOLISP interactor, which is always at the bottom
of the stack.

** D7. One AutoLISP registration API + a registry.

- =(clal-define-command "INTERACTOR-NAME" NAMES FUNCTION [DOC])=
  registers into the named interactor's user dictionary.
  =clal-define-debugger-command= becomes a deprecated equivalent of
  ="ALDO"=.
- =(clal-list-interactor-names)= returns the names of ALL registered
  interactors (e.g. ("AUTOLISP" "ALDO" "NAVI" "LAVI" "INSPECT"
  "SEDIT")), whether stacked or not: commands are installed before
  their interactor is activated.
- DEFINE-INTERACTOR populates the name -> interactor registry.

** D8. Routing is stack-only.

=NAME CMD …= routes only to interactors ON the current stack. The
stack is dynamic and an interactor may need activation state, so
invoking a command of an inactive interactor is not meaningful. (The
registry is for registration and listing, not routing.)

** D9. Stack manipulation replaces nested loops where possible.

- =clal-sedit= pushes SEDIT on the stack.
- navi <-> lavi swap by pop+push.
- =q= in a pushed mode pops it.
- A NESTED loop remains only for invoke-debugger (=ui-await-command=
  must return the resume directive to the engine; ON-RESULT +
  INTERACTOR-RETURN carry a debugger command's non-nil value out from
  however deep a mode it was issued).

* Tensions and inconsistencies to resolve

** T1. Same-loop mode switching vs dynamic-variable activation state.

D2 (context via dynamics) and D9 (push/pop within the SAME loop)
conflict for *mode-local* state: a command that pushes NAVI cannot
LET-bind =*navi-state*= for the duration of the mode — the binding's
extent ends when the command returns. Dynamic binding only brackets a
mode when entering it runs a nested loop, which D9 wants to avoid.

Yet some state is genuinely per-activation, not per-interactor: NAVI's
current location + redraw flag, LAVI's line cursor — and a nested
invoke-debugger can suspend one NAVI activation under another, so a
mutable slot on the singleton would be clobbered.

Proposed resolution: the stack holds ACTIVATIONS, not bare
interactors — each entry pairs (INTERACTOR . STATE), like a call frame
pairs a function with its locals. PUSH-INTERACTOR takes the optional
initial state; the loop binds =*command-interactor*= (and the owning
activation's state) around each command; prompt/status/reader/
evaluator receive (or read dynamically) the current activation's
state. Interactors stay singleton programs (D1), recursion is safe,
and push/pop works in the same loop (D9). [pjb to confirm]

** T2. Does the stack design retire sedit's internal NAV/EDIT modes?

sedit-spec §6.6 defines sedit's own two-mode machine: NAV mode
(motions only, prompt =NAV>=, deliberately collision-free so debugger
verbs pass bare) vs EDIT mode (prompt =SEDIT>=, where =i a r c x v z
m= are insert/add/replace/copy/cut/paste/undo/macroexpand — colliding
with the debugger's into/advance/return/continue/visit; hence "the
debugger needs the =debug=/=aldo= prefix" in EDIT).

Under the stack model the mode distinction is naturally "which
interactor is on top", and the prefix rule falls out of shadowing +
=aldo CMD= routing — no special machinery. But D5 says SEDIT's motions
are its own commands (all-sub-sexp traversal), so SEDIT-the-interactor
plausibly carries motions AND editing keys in one dictionary. Then:

- Option A — ONE SEDIT interactor (motions + editing keys together,
  prompt =SEDIT>= always). Simple; but =i a r c v= then ALWAYS shadow
  the debugger while sedit is stacked — sedit-NAV's collision-free
  property (and the =NAV>= prompt inside sedit) disappears; §6.6 would
  be amended accordingly.
- Option B — TWO stacked interactors (=*sedit-nav*= motions-only,
  collision-free; =*sedit*= editing); =edit=/=nav= push/pop between
  them. Preserves §6.6 semantics exactly as stack behavior.

The discussion so far leans A (the two-mode machine dissolves into the
stack) but §6/§6.6 of the sedit spec then needs a normative amendment.
[pjb to decide]

** T3. Shared command functions need one fixed calling convention.

D5's reuse of one function by several interactors' commands requires
that the function get its context uniformly — it cannot rely on a
mode-specific wrapper macro. Convention to fix: a command function
receives its parsed arguments per its declared lambda-list (or the raw
string under =(&whole arg)=), and reaches everything else through
dynamics — =*debugger-ui*= / =*debugger-session*= / =*debugger-hit*=
and the owning activation's state (T1). The DEFINE-*-COMMAND mode
macros remain as sugar producing such functions inline.

** T4. Leaving ALDO is not a pop.

=q= uniformly pops a pushed mode (NAVI/LAVI/INSPECT/SEDIT). But ALDO's
activation is tied to a STOP: leaving it means resolving the stop with
a directive (=q= -> abort, =c=/=i=/… -> resume), carried out of the
nested loop by ON-RESULT/INTERACTOR-RETURN — not popping. This
asymmetry is intentional (D9) but must stay documented, or =aldo=
lingering on a stack after its stop would be routable with a dead
session.

** T5. Tests currently rebind =*global-dictionary*=.

With D6 the variable disappears; tests that rebind it to isolate user
commands must instead swap =(interactor-user-commands *aldo*)= (or a
with-fresh-user-dictionary helper). Mechanical, but part of the D6
change, not separable.

** T6. LAVI's name.

D4 makes LAVI a peer interactor, but the name list in D7 needs it
included (and its display name decided: "LAVI"?) so
=clal-list-interactor-names= and =NAME CMD= routing agree. [pjb to
confirm the name]

* Implementation order (after revision)

1. T1 resolution: activations on the stack; kill COPY-INTERACTOR uses
   and the struct STATE slot; singleton templates keep everything else.
2. D2: the unified read-eval-print with live dialect dispatch; all
   evaluators route through it.
3. D6/D7/D8: retire =*global-dictionary*=; registry; =clal-define-command=
   + =clal-list-interactor-names=; deprecate =clal-define-debugger-command=.
4. D3: AUTOLISP/LISP naming.
5. D5/T3: =:function= registration sugar + the documented calling
   convention.
6. T2 decision, then SEDIT onto the stack (D9: =clal-sedit= pushes it),
   with the sedit-spec amendment.
